This solution uses a depth-first search (DFS) approach to explore all possible ways to split the string `s` into unique substrings. The function `dfs` is a recursive helper function that tries to split the string starting from index `i`. It uses a set `st` to keep track of the unique substrings found so far. The variable `ans` keeps track of the maximum number of unique substrings found during the search. The function returns the maximum number of unique substrings that the string `s` can be split into.
